Data

For the following examples, we will be working on 2 datasets: iris and Table_TPMs.

Load iris dataset

R contains datasets to work as example data. Here we load a data set called âirisâ, with measurements on 3 iris species.

data("iris")

paged_table(iris)

Read expression data from csv

We load the TPM table resulting from a mRNA-seq analysis on D. melanogaster in 3 control samples and 3 treated samples. To reduce computing time, the file only contains 100 genes (out of ~15,000).

Table_TPMs<-read.csv("data/TPMs_table_100genes.csv",row.names=1)
class(Table_TPMs)
[1] "data.frame"
paged_table(Table_TPMs)

Scatter plots

For this section we will use iris dataset.

The base R function plot() expects to get y and x values.

We can plot the scatter plot of petalâs length vs with.

plot(x=iris$Sepal.Length, y=iris$Sepal.Width)

  • Same way, we can now plot Petal length depending on Petal width (we can omit x= and y=).
plot(iris$Petal.Length ,iris$Petal.Width)

  • We will also often plot y in function of x as y~x.
plot(iris$Petal.Width ~ iris$Petal.Length)

The plot function will try to adjust the plot to the data. If x variable is categorical (e.g.Â Species) and the other y continuous (e.g. Sepal.Length) will make a boxplot.

Boxplots

Here, we will use the TPMs data from gene expression.

Letâs make a boxlot in base R. Showing for each sample, the expression of all genes in it.

boxplot(Table_TPMs)

Letâs put labels on the axes, and title:

boxplot(Table_TPMs, col="lightblue", border="darkgrey",  ylab="TPMs", xlab="Sample Name", main="Boxplot gene expression per sample in TPMs")

Remove outliers.

boxplot(Table_TPMs, col="lightblue", border="darkgrey", outline=FALSE, ylab="TPMs", xlab="Sample Name", main="Boxplot gene expression per sample in TPMs")

Barplots

Fer example, we want to plot the mean of the TPMs per sample. First we compute the mean, and then we plot it as barplot.

meanTMS_table<-colMeans(Table_TPMs)
meanTMS_table
Control_1 Control_2 Control_3 Treated_1 Treated_2 Treated_3 
 70.27366  82.00448  79.38437  83.44722  78.91726  76.17010

After calculating means we can plot it

barplot(meanTMS_table, ylab="Mean TPMs", xlab="Sample")

For the iris dataset, we would do the something similar:

mean_measurements_pers_pp = aggregate(iris[,1:4], by = list(iris$Species), FUN = mean)
mean_measurements_pers_pp
     Group.1 Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width
1     setosa        5.006       3.428        1.462       0.246
2 versicolor        5.936       2.770        4.260       1.326
3  virginica        6.588       2.974        5.552       2.026
barplot(mean_measurements_pers_pp$Petal.Length~mean_measurements_pers_pp$Group.1, ylab="Mean Sepal Length", xlab="Species of Iris")

Export plots

Steps:

  1. Open output file (define format).
  2. Make plot.
  3. Close file.

Example of how to export in png:

  • You need to run all chunk code once (Ctrl+Shift+Enter) or select from png() to dev.off() and Ctrl+Enter.
# Open a png ( set the desired size and resolution)
png("images/My_first_plot.png",  width = 10, height=10, units = "cm", res = 300)  
# Create a plot
plot(iris$Petal.Length ~ iris$Sepal.Length, col="cadetblue4", pch = 17)
# Close file
dev.off()

## Data

For the following examples, we will be working on 2 datasets: **iris**
and **Table_TPMs**.

### Load iris dataset

R contains datasets to work as example data. Here we load a data set
called "iris", with measurements on 3 iris species.

```{r}
data("iris")

paged_table(iris)
```

![](images/clipboard-4018340327.png)

### Read expression data from csv

We load the TPM table resulting from a mRNA-seq analysis on *D.
melanogaster* in 3 control samples and 3 treated samples. To reduce
computing time, the file only contains 100 genes (out of \~15,000).

```{r}
Table_TPMs<-read.csv("data/TPMs_table_100genes.csv",row.names=1)
class(Table_TPMs)
paged_table(Table_TPMs)
```

## Scatter plots

For this section we will use **iris** dataset.

The base R function `plot()` expects to get y and x values.

We can plot the scatter plot of petal's length vs with.

```{r}
plot(x=iris$Sepal.Length, y=iris$Sepal.Width)
```

-   Same way, we can now plot Petal length depending on Petal width (we
    can omit x= and y=).

```{r}
plot(iris$Petal.Length ,iris$Petal.Width)
```

-   We will also often plot y in function of x as **y\~x**.

```{r}
plot(iris$Petal.Width ~ iris$Petal.Length)
```

### Solution Exercise 1 {style="background-color: #e7fccc"}

```{r}
plot(iris$Petal.Length~iris$Species)
```

The `plot` function will try to adjust the plot to the data. If x
variable is categorical (e.g. Species) and the other y continuous (e.g.
Sepal.Length) will make a boxplot.

## Boxplots

Here, we will use the **TPMs data from gene expression**.

Let's make a boxlot in base R. Showing for each sample, the expression
of all genes in it.

```{r}
boxplot(Table_TPMs)
```

Let's put labels on the axes, and title:

```{r}
boxplot(Table_TPMs, col="lightblue", border="darkgrey",  ylab="TPMs", xlab="Sample Name", main="Boxplot gene expression per sample in TPMs")
```

Remove outliers.

```{r}
boxplot(Table_TPMs, col="lightblue", border="darkgrey", outline=FALSE, ylab="TPMs", xlab="Sample Name", main="Boxplot gene expression per sample in TPMs")
```

## Barplots

Fer example, we want to plot the mean of the TPMs per sample. First we
compute the mean, and then we plot it as barplot.

```{r}
meanTMS_table<-colMeans(Table_TPMs)
meanTMS_table
```

After calculating means we can plot it

```{r}
barplot(meanTMS_table, ylab="Mean TPMs", xlab="Sample")
```

For the **iris** dataset, we would do the something similar:

```{r}
mean_measurements_pers_pp = aggregate(iris[,1:4], by = list(iris$Species), FUN = mean)
mean_measurements_pers_pp

```

```{r}
barplot(mean_measurements_pers_pp$Petal.Length~mean_measurements_pers_pp$Group.1, ylab="Mean Sepal Length", xlab="Species of Iris")
```

## Export plots

Steps:

1.  Open output file (define format).
2.  Make plot.
3.  Close file.

Example of how to export in png:

-   You need to run all chunk code once (**Ctrl+Shift+Enter**) or select
    from png() to dev.off() and Ctrl+Enter.

```{r}
# Open a png ( set the desired size and resolution)
png("images/My_first_plot.png",  width = 10, height=10, units = "cm", res = 300)  
# Create a plot
plot(iris$Petal.Length ~ iris$Sepal.Length, col="cadetblue4", pch = 17)
# Close file
dev.off() 
```

### Solution Exercise 4 {style="background-color: #e7fccc"}

```{r}

#| output: true

# I set up 100 breaks to see it more granular
dev.off()
```
